+// Copyright (c) TriDB. Licensed under the MIT License.
+//
+// tjs_operator.cpp — TriDB Traversal-Join-Similarity (TJS) operator (DEV-1169 / FR-4).
+//
+// Marker for the patch sentinel grep (scripts/lib/msvbase_patches.sh): TRIDB: TJS operator.
+//
+// WHAT THIS IS
+// ------------
+// TJS composes all THREE TriDB modalities — graph traversal, relational filter, and vector
+// similarity — in ONE Volcano plan with a SINGLE global, early-terminating top-k. It is the
+// keystone the whole "tri-modal in one process, one query" thesis rests on (CLAUDE.md TR-1 /
+// golden rule 4, spec §5). It is a forked, generalized execFagins (the topk.cpp / multicol_topk.cpp
+// Fagin-merge): it builds a child HNSW IndexScan via SPI exactly like multicol_topk (enable_seqscan
+// off, extractIndexScanNode, ExecProcNode), reads the TRUE per-candidate distance from
+// node->iss_ScanDesc->xs_orderbyvals[0] (the ONLY authoritative distance — the fork's scalar `<->`
+// returns 0 outside an index scan; see test/trimodal_early_term.sql), and terminates early on
+// consecutive_drops >= term_cond.
+//
+// THE THREE LEGS (synthesis decision, ADR-0007)
+// ---------------------------------------------
+//   VECTOR leg   — the HNSW IndexScan built via SPI. xs_orderbyvals[0] is the SOLE rank authority.
+//                  This is the one ordered stream; everything else is a predicate on it.
+//   RELATIONAL   — the filter is pushed INTO the vector leg's SQL WHERE (multicol_topk already
+//                  builds `select ... from <t> where <filter> order by <orderby>`), so the index
+//                  scan never even emits filtered-out rows.
+//   GRAPH        — a reachability PREDICATE on each vector candidate: is candidate dst reachable
+//                  (src)-[:related_to]->(dst)? We probe graph_store.neighbors(src) via SPI ONCE at
+//                  init and cache the reachable-id set, then test membership at the seen-set point
+//                  in the merge. Probing once (not interleaved with the SPI-driven IndexScan) avoids
+//                  nesting a second SPI cursor inside the executor-driven scan — the reachable set is
+//                  finite, so caching it is exact, not an approximation.
+//
+// Because graph + relational are PREDICATES on the single ordered (vector) stream — not a second
+// ordered stream to merge — there is no order-merge to reconcile, and the VBASE consecutive_drops
+// early-termination stays correct: a candidate that fails the graph or relational predicate simply
+// is not inserted into the result priority queue, exactly like a candidate that loses on distance.
+//
+// TR-1 (CLAUDE.md golden rule 1): Open/Next/Close + EARLY TERMINATION, no blocking operator. The
+// bounded priority queue is size k; the merge stops once consecutive_drops >= term_cond and then
+// Close()s the children (ExecutorFinish/End on each child QueryDesc), propagating the stop into the
+// HNSW beam. The merge does NOT materialize the full corpus — it drains the ANN stream only until
+// the top-k is provably settled, the same bound multicol_topk relies on.
+//
+// SRF-NOW / CUSTOMSCAN-LATER: this ships as a C SRF tjs(...) registered like multicol_topk (NOT a
+// CustomScan, which would couple to the unfinished parser). execTJS() is a pure
+// `TupleTableSlot* execTJS(PlanState*)` so a future CustomScan node can reuse it verbatim — the SRF
+// is just a thin driver around it. See docs/decisions/0007-tjs-operator.md.
+
